<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06160190 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06160190 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  BANK; BUSINESS; END; FORECAST; NORTH; EAST; US  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  As many as 20 New England banks with combined assets of $30 billion areexpected to fail in the next year, and the failures will be far worse if theregion's economy remains in a prolonged recession, banking experts warned thisweek.;    In the year ahead, &quot;we'll have enough failures to equal in size thefailures we've had to date,&quot; predicted Thomas Cimeno, senior vice president ofthe Federal Reserve Bank of Boston.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MORE TROUBLE SEEN FOR NEW ENGLAND BANKS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Cimeno's prediction was the first estimate by such a high-level source ofhow bad the New England banking crisis might get.;    In the past year, NewEngland has lost 36 banks with combined assets of $29 billion, including theBank of New England, which accounted for about two-thirds of the total.;   Cimeno said he is not predicting another big New England bank will go under.But &quot;20 mid-sized institutions isn't out of the question by any means,&quot; hetold economists and business leaders at a meeting in Newton, Mass., of the NewEngland Economic Project, a regional research group.;    Another bankingexpert, however, warned that if the New England recession drags on for another18 months, several of the biggest banks in the region could collapse.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Washington Post  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910608  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.COL>  14E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  202  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday June 8, 199100160190,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>